Bike Share Analysis

The bike share company make most of their profit from annual memberships.
The marketing team wants to maximize annual membership by targeting casual riders.
Before making this decision, they want to make sure how casual riders and annual members
ride their bike differently by providing data insights and visualizations.
By cleaning and analyzing data, it can provide some insights to why casual riders
buy annual memberships.

The minimum ride_length from casual and members were 0 .

day_of_week is in numbers. I changed the numbers into days to make it easier understand.

aggregate(all_trips$ride_length~all_trips$member_casual,FUN = min)

converted numbers to days.

all_trips <- all_trips %>%
  mutate(day_of_week = recode(day_of_week
                              ,"1"="Sunday"
                              ,"2"="Monday"
                              ,"3"="Tuesday"
                              ,"4"="Wednesday"
                              ,"5"= "Thursday"
                              ,"6"="Friday"
                              ,"7"= "Saturday"))

Visualization

Counting Annual members and casual riders.

There are more number of annual members than casual riders.

ggplot(all_trips,aes(x=member_casual,fill=as.factor(member_casual)))+
  geom_bar(color="grey40")+
  geom_text(aes(label=..count..),stat="count",vjust=1.5)+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("pink","orange"))+
  labs(title="Number of Casual Riders and Annual Members")

Number of Rides During the Week.

Annual members ride more often than casual riders during the weekdays. But, casual riders

ride more during the weekends.

all_trips %>%
  group_by(day_of_week,member_casual)%>%
  summarise(count=n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=day_of_week,y=count, fill=member_casual,label=count)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity",position="dodge",color="grey40") +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#a1e9f0","#d9b1f0"))+
  geom_text(aes(label=count),position=position_dodge(width= 0.8),hjust=1.2,family="Georgia") +
  labs(title="Number of Rides During the Week") +
  coord_flip()
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'day_of_week'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Mean ride length for annual members and casual riders.

In this bar chart, casual riders ride longer than casual members.

all_trips %>%
  group_by(member_casual, day_of_week) %>%
  summarise(average_duration=mean(ride_length,na.rm=T)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=day_of_week,y=average_duration,fill=member_casual)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity",position="dodge",color="grey40") +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#69b3a2","#9E9AC8"))+
  geom_col(position=position_dodge()) +
  labs(title="Average Ride Length During the Week")+
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90,hjust=1))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'member_casual'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Since the time is converted into numeric, maximum average ride length was 1890 by casual riders on sunday.

1890 is about 31 mins and 40 sec. Whereas 1500 is about 25 mins and all the annual memebers seem to be

closest from 800 to 900 this ranges from 13 mins to 15 mins. (1000 is 16mins and 40sec)

aggregate(all_trips$ride_length~all_trips$day_of_week+all_trips$member_casual,FUN=mean)
data.table::as.ITime(1900)
[1] "00:31:40"
data.table::as.ITime(1500)
[1] "00:25:00"
data.table::as.ITime(1000)
[1] "00:16:40"
data.table::as.ITime(900)
[1] "00:15:00"

Conclusion

As displayed on the graph, casual riders have higher average ride length compared to annual members,while

annual members tend to ride more during the week, but casual riders tend to ride more annual members on weekends.Hence, promotion during the weekends can help increase annual memberships.
